 with a focus on the films’ fundamentally experimental and inventive character. By considering films and production contexts often neglected in film studies, it strives to counter the still dominant view of the transitional period as a time of yet-to-be-perfected forerunners of ‘classical’ sound film. Instead, authors highlight the sense of ‘fruitful uncertainty’ in this period of media change and transformation. Subjects covered include visual and auditory style; the uses of speech, music, and noises; aesthetic conceptions in sound film theory; and intermedial aesthetics. The volume’s scope is decidedly international, covering production and reception contexts in the Soviet Union, Japan, the USA, Germany, France, Italy, the UK, and Switzerland.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aSound motion picturesxHistory. 4aFilm Studies. 4aFilm, Media, and Communication. 4aHistory. 4aMedia Studies. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / General.2bisacsh  aFilm history, film aesthetics, media change, film sound.1 aAdorno, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBarnier, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerry, Jessica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBulgakowa, Oksana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrafton, Donald, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoltz, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJacobs, Lea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLeimbacher, Irina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLoew, Katharina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNordström, Johan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul